{"cursor":"3796","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Stream of consciousness' refers to the flow of thoughts in the conscious mind.\nThe full range of thoughts that one can be aware of can form the content of this\nstream, not just verbal thoughts. Commonly used experimental techniques,\nincluding self-reporting, gives easier access to verbal thoughts than to\nthoughts more closely connected to senses other than hearing and activities\nother than speaking and writing.\n","linknr":130,"url":"Stream_of_consciousness_(psychology)","recorded":1362373675,"links":10,"instances":["psychology"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Consciousness studies","Cognition"],"headings":["Buddhism","Proponents","Criticism","Literary technique","See also","References","External links"],"image":["//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/vector/images/search-ltr.png?303-4","//bits.wikimedia.org/images/wikimedia-button.png","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/poweredby_mediawiki_88x31.png"],"tags":[["phenomenology","psychology"]],"members":["phenomenology"],"related":["Thought","Consciousness","Mind","Awareness","Internal_monologue","Self-reporting","Pali","Pali_Canon","Digha_Nikaya","Yogachara","Mahayana_Buddhism","Hammalawa_Saddhatissa","Theravada","Anatta","William_James","Introspection","George_Armitage_Miller","Bernard_Baars","Global_Workspace_Theory","Susan_Blackmore","Stream_of_consciousness_writing","Literary_device","May_Sinclair","Free_recall","Edmund_Husserl","Phenomenology_(psychology)","Qualia","Train_of_thought","Samyama"]}